# 1️⃣ Concept Teaching (Strict, Clear, GATE-Oriented)

---

# 🔹 What is Parallelism?

Parallelism means:

👉 Performing multiple operations simultaneously
👉 Improves system performance

Modern processors use:

* Multiple cores
* Pipelines
* Parallel execution units

---

# 🔹 Types of Parallelism

---

## 1️⃣ Instruction Level Parallelism (ILP)

Multiple instructions executed simultaneously.

Example:

* Pipelining
* Superscalar processors

---

## 2️⃣ Data Level Parallelism (DLP)

Same operation on multiple data items.

Example:

* Vector processing
* SIMD

---

## 3️⃣ Task Level Parallelism (TLP)

Different tasks executed in parallel.

Example:

* Multithreading
* Multicore CPUs

---

# 🔹 Flynn’s Classification (VERY IMPORTANT)

Based on:

* Instruction streams
* Data streams

---

## 1️⃣ SISD

Single Instruction Single Data

👉 Traditional sequential computer.

---

## 2️⃣ SIMD

Single Instruction Multiple Data

👉 Same instruction on multiple data.

Example:

* GPU
* Vector processors

---

## 3️⃣ MISD

Multiple Instruction Single Data

Rarely used.

---

## 4️⃣ MIMD

Multiple Instruction Multiple Data

👉 Modern multicore systems.

---

# 🔹 Performance Metrics

---

## 🔹 CPU Execution Time

[
CPU\ Time = Instruction\ Count \times CPI \times Clock\ Cycle\ Time
]

OR

[
CPU\ Time = \frac{Instruction\ Count \times CPI}{Clock\ Rate}
]

📌 Very important formula.

---

# 🔹 CPI (Cycles Per Instruction)

Average clock cycles per instruction.

Lower CPI → better performance.

---

# 🔹 MIPS

[
MIPS = \frac{Instruction\ Count}{Execution\ Time \times 10^6}
]

Million Instructions Per Second.

📌 Not always reliable for comparison.

---

# 🔹 Speedup

[
Speedup = \frac{Old\ Execution\ Time}{New\ Execution\ Time}
]

---

# 🔹 Amdahl’s Law (VERY IMPORTANT)

Limits maximum speedup due to serial portion.

[
Speedup = \frac{1}{(1-f)+\frac{f}{n}}
]

Where:

* f = parallelizable fraction
* n = processors

📌 Major GATE favorite.

---

# 🔹 Throughput vs Latency

| Throughput               | Latency           |
| ------------------------ | ----------------- |
| Tasks completed per time | Time for one task |

📌 Parallelism improves throughput more.

---

# 🔹 Superscalar Architecture

CPU issues multiple instructions per clock cycle.

📌 Uses ILP.

---

# 🔹 Multicore Processor

Multiple CPUs on same chip.

Improves:

* Parallel execution
* Performance

---

# 🔹 Common GATE Traps

* Confusing throughput & latency
* Wrong Amdahl’s law calculation
* Mixing SIMD & MIMD

